diff:1620447291:1620447291:=1,44d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Expansion: %0a%3c :Author: AlexX%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.MockingOfHarryKanesAccent|MockingOfHarryKanesAccent]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.SubhasishM|SubhasishM]]%0a%3c :Section: B%0a%3c :Completed: 07.05.2021 - 21:14%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c As a fan of Tottenham and Harry Kane himself, I must admit that I myself have in the past laughed at and made jokes about his accent and speech patterns without understanding or giving much thought to the full context behind them, especially the stigmatization of his accent in English society. I completely agree with your assessment of the ESPN clip - to reduce one of the most talented soccer players of the past decade to his accent is very upsetting and a textbook example of linguistic discrimination. %0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2015/10/06/wayne-rooney-bbc-documentary-scouse-accent-subtitles%0a%3c %0a%3c Very similar to Harry Kane, Wayne Rooney, another well-known English soccer player, has for years been the subject of considerable ridicule for his heavy scouse accent. The scouse accent, originating from the city of Liverpool, is one of the most stigmatized accents in England; it is considered to be of low prestige, and is often associated with lack of education and poverty. Hence, it is no surprise that Rooney, a high-profile celebrity, has been mocked widely and with impunity by the media and the public alike for his accent. %0a%3c %0a%3c Overall, the mocking of soccer players' accents seems to be a microcosm of the dynamics of language contact in England, where a traditionally rigid social hierarchy seems to have instilled an equally rigid hierarchy of accents.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
